The dissociation energy from the bottom of the potential well, \(D_e\), is related to the dissociation energy from the ground vibrational level, \(D_0\), by the zero-point energy (ZPE). The ZPE is calculated using the spectroscopic constants \(\omega_e = \nu_e / c = 1405.65  \text{cm}^{-1}\) and \(\omega_e x_e = \nu_e x_e / c = 23.20  \text{cm}^{-1}\).

The formula for ZPE in wavenumber units is:
\[
\text{ZPE} = \frac{1}{2} \omega_e - \frac{1}{4} \omega_e x_e
\]
Substituting the given values:
\[
\text{ZPE} = \frac{1}{2} \times 1405.65 - \frac{1}{4} \times 23.20 = 702.825 - 5.80 = 697.025  \text{cm}^{-1}
\]

Convert ZPE to eV using the conversion factor \(1  \text{cm}^{-1} = \frac{1}{8065.54}  \text{eV}\):
\[
\text{ZPE}_{\text{eV}} = 697.025 / 8065.54 \approx 0.086420  \text{eV}
\]

Now, calculate \(D_e\):
\[
D_e = D_0 + \text{ZPE}_{\text{eV}} = 2.4287 + 0.086420 = 2.515120  \text{eV}
\]

