Problem: A doctor is concerned about the relationship between blood pressure and irregular heartbeats. Among her patients, she classifies blood pressures as high, normal, or low and heartbeats as regular or irregular and finds that 16\% have high blood pressure; (b) 19\% have low blood pressure; (c) $17 \%$ have an irregular heartbeat; (d) of those with an irregular heartbeat, $35 \%$ have high blood pressure; and (e) of those with normal blood pressure, $11 \%$ have an irregular heartbeat. What percentage of her patients have a regular heartbeat and low blood pressure? The unit of the answer should be % .
Solution: To find the percentage of patients with a regular heartbeat and low blood pressure, the given information is used to calculate the joint probabilities step by step.

- 16% of patients have high blood pressure (H).
- 19% have low blood pressure (L).
- 17% have an irregular heartbeat (I).
- Of those with an irregular heartbeat, 35% have high blood pressure: \( P(H \mid I) = 35\% \).
- Of those with normal blood pressure (N), 11% have an irregular heartbeat: \( P(I \mid N) = 11\% \).

First, the percentage with normal blood pressure is calculated:  
\( P(N) = 100\% - P(H) - P(L) = 100\% - 16\% - 19\% = 65\% \).

Next, the joint probabilities involving irregular heartbeat are computed:  
- \( P(H \text{ and } I) = P(H \mid I) \times P(I) = 35\% \times 17\% = 0.35 \times 0.17 = 0.0595 = 5.95\% \).  
- \( P(I \text{ and } N) = P(I \mid N) \times P(N) = 11\% \times 65\% = 0.11 \times 0.65 = 0.0715 = 7.15\% \).

The total irregular heartbeat percentage must equal the sum of irregular heartbeat across all blood pressure categories:  
\( P(I) = P(I \text{ and } H) + P(I \text{ and } N) + P(I \text{ and } L) \).  
