Problem: Calculate the energy of one mole of UV photons of wavelength $300 \mathrm{~nm}$ and compare it with a typical single-bond energy of $400 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$. The unit of the answer should be  $\mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$.
Solution: The energy of one mole of photons is calculated using the formula \(E = \frac{hcN_A}{\lambda}\), where \(h = 6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s}\), \(c = 3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s}\), \(N_A = 6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}\), and \(\lambda = 300 \, \text{nm} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}\).

First, compute \(hc\):  
\(hc = (6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8) = 1.9878 \times 10^{-25} \, \text{J·m}\).

Then, compute \(hcN_A\):  
\(hcN_A = (1.9878 \times 10^{-25}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23}) = 0.119705316 \, \text{J·m/mol}\).

Now, divide by \(\lambda\):  
\(E = \frac{0.119705316}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 399017.72 \, \text{J/mol}\).

Convert to kJ/mol:  
\(399017.72 \, \text{J/mol} \div 1000 = 399.01772 \, \text{kJ/mol}\).

Rounding to three significant figures (since the wavelength is given as 300 nm with three significant figures), the energy is \(399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\).

Comparison: The energy of the UV photons (\(399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\)) is very close to the typical single-bond energy of \(400 \, \text{kJ/mol}\), indicating that photons of this wavelength have sufficient energy to break such bonds.

Summary: The final answer is $399$
